\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. M. fruticosa} (L.) Druce,{\i  Rep. Bot. Exch. Club Brit. Is. }{\b 3}: 421 (1914) ({\i M. marifolia} (Cav.) Bentham). Dwarf shrub 30-60 cm, minutely whitish-velutinous; branches divaricate. Leaves 5-20 × 2-12 mm, lanceolate to ovate-orbicular, entire to weakly sinuate or dentate, flat. Verticillasters with 10-30(-50) flowers, lax, greatly exceeding subtending leaves. Calyx (1·5-)2·5-3·5 mm, obovoid-tubular to obconic, densely villous in throat; teeth c. ¼ as long as tube, triangular, equal. Corolla 5-10 mm, whitish. Nutlets obtuse.{\i  Usually calcicole. E. Spain; C. Italy; S.W. Jugoslavia; Krym.} ?Gr Hs It Ju Rs (K).
\par

\par
 ({\b a}) Subsp. {\b fruticosa} : Leaves strongly punctate beneath. Calyx and pedicels velutinous; calyx obovoid-tubular. •{\i  E. Spain; C. Italy}.
\par
 ({\b b}) Subsp. {\b serpyllifolia}  (Bieb.) P. H. Davis,{\i  Kew Bull.} [6]: 77 (1951) ({\i M. serpyllifolia }(Bieb.) Boiss.): Leaves not punctate beneath. Calyx and pedicels puberulent; calyx obconic.{\i  Krym; S.W. Jugoslavia.} ({\i S.W. Asia}.)
\par

